Under the null hypothesis (H0), no de novo mutations within the gene of interest contribute to disease risk. This implies that the probability of having a disease-causal de novo mutation is 0, or formally, Pr(Dij|r,m) = 0 for all values of i and j. Given Pr(Dij|r,m) = rm and m ≠ 0, we have r = 0. Conversely, r = 0 suggests that the relative mutation rate of disease-causing mutations to risk-neutral mutations is 0 (by definition), and therefore no disease-causing de novo mutation can occur. We can apply a likelihood ratio test to calculate the following test statistic:\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
